1. The Lab Exam Script (flickr6.sh)

First, fetch a test file on your command line so you can test locally:
Bash

wget -q -O feed.json "https://api.flickr.com/services/feeds/photos_public.gne?format=json&tags=dublin"

Next, create your script: nano flickr6.sh

The character you need to remove using tr is the backslash (\). In JSON, HTML characters like quotes (") and forward slashes (/) are "escaped" by putting a backslash in front of them (e.g., \" and \/). Deleting all backslashes instantly converts the encoded JSON strings back into valid, readable HTML.

Here is the complete script for Einstein:
Bash

#!/bin/bash

# Define the extra spacing and title HTML
EXTRA="<hr style='margin-top:70'><h1> next photo </h1>"

# Redirect all script output to the required file
exec > "$HOME/flickr.html"

# Process the local JSON feed
cat feed.json | \
egrep '"description":|"tags":' | \
tr -d '\\' | \
sed -e "s|<p>|$EXTRA<p>|"

How it works:

    exec > "$HOME/flickr.html" captures everything that would normally print to the screen and writes it to the HTML file.

    egrep '"description":|"tags":' filters the file down to only the lines containing the image payloads and their associated tags.

    tr -d '\\' deletes the backslashes, decoding the HTML snippets so the browser can render the images. (Note: We use \\ because bash uses the backslash as an escape character itself, so we have to escape the escape character).

    sed -e "s|<p>|$EXTRA<p>|" finds the first instance of a <p> tag on each line and injects the $EXTRA formatting right before it. By omitting the g flag at the end of the sed command, it ensures this replacement only happens once per line, keeping Einstein happy.

Make it executable and test:
Bash

chmod +x flickr6.sh
./flickr6.sh

2. The Real-World Script (flickr)

Once you pass the Einstein tests, you can create a dynamic version of the script that accepts any tag, downloads the feed on the fly, and generates the page.

Create this in your $HOME/bin directory: nano $HOME/bin/flickr
Bash

#!/bin/bash

# Check if the user provided a tag
if [ -z "$1" ]; then
    echo "Usage: flickr <tag> (e.g., flickr paris)"
    exit 1
fi

EXTRA="<hr style='margin-top:70'><h1> next photo </h1>"

# Redirect output to the HTML file
exec > "$HOME/flickr.html"

# Fetch the feed directly using the command-line argument ($1)
# The URL must be in quotes because the '&' character will break the shell command otherwise
URL="https://api.flickr.com/services/feeds/photos_public.gne?format=json&tags=$1"

wget -q -O - "$URL" | \
egrep '"description":|"tags":' | \
tr -d '\\' | \
sed -e "s|<p>|$EXTRA<p>|"

# Output a success message to the screen (by sending it to standard error)
echo "Webpage generated at $HOME/flickr.html" >&2

Make it executable:
Bash

chmod +x $HOME/bin/flickr

You can now run flickr belfast or flickr dogs from anywhere, and it will instantly build a gallery of the latest photos to $HOME/flickr.html.
